[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    822[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 3: Per-Patient Discharge Probability Over the Horizon
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    823[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    824[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For every currently-admitted patient, predict the probability they discharge in each hour of the forecast horizon. A real survival model takes the per-patient features and produces a hazard function over the horizon. The demo uses an exponential survival model with a per-service-line baseline rate, a discharge-order multiplier, and an hour-of-day multiplier so the simulated discharge times concentrate in the typical 13:00-15:00 peak. Production swaps this for a Cox proportional hazards model, an XGBoost survival model (XGBSE), or a deep survival model like DeepHit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    825[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    826[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    827[0m:[38;5;10m[49m class ExponentialSurvivalModel:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    828[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """Pedagogical exponential survival model for hospital discharge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    829[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    830[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Production fits a Cox proportional hazards model (lifelines
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    831[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     or scikit-survival), an XGBoost survival model (XGBSE), or a
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    832[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     deep survival model (DeepHit, PySurvival) on per-patient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    833[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features. The demo computes the hazard analytically:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    834[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    835[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hazard(h) = baseline_hazard(service_line)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    836[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     * discharge_order_multiplier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    837[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     * hour_of_day_intensity(target_hour)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    838[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    839[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     where baseline_hazard is the inverse of the service-line's
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    840[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     expected total LOS, discharge_order_multiplier is 6.0 if the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    841[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     order is in (and 1.0 otherwise), and hour_of_day_intensity is
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    842[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     the relative discharge intensity at the target hour-of-day.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    843[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The hazard is converted to a per-hour discharge probability
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    844[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     via the standard exponential decay formula.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    845[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    846[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    847[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     name = "exp_survival"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    848[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    849[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     def __init__(self,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    850[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  service_los_hours,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    851[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  hour_of_day_intensity,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    852[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  discharge_order_multiplier):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    853[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.service_los_hours       = service_los_hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    854[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.hour_of_day_intensity   = hour_of_day_intensity
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    855[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.discharge_order_multiplier = discharge_order_multiplier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    856[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    857[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     def hazard_per_hour(self, features, target_hour_of_day):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    858[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         """Compute the discharge hazard rate for one hour."""
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    859[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         service = features["service_line"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    860[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         baseline_los = self.service_los_hours.get(service, 96.0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    861[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         baseline_hazard = 1.0 / baseline_los
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    862[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    863[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Patients past their service-line LOS have a slightly
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    864[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # elevated hazard (they are statistically due to discharge
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    865[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # any hour now). Patients earlier in their stay have a
